===Verb===
{{en-verb|ador}}

#To [[worship]].
#*{{w|Tobias Smollett}} (1721–1771)
#*:Bishops and priests,{{...}}bearing the host, which he [James] publicly '''adored'''.
#To [[love]] with one's entire heart and soul; regard with deep [[respect]] and [[affection]].
#:{{ux|en|It is obvious to everyone that Gerry '''adores''' Heather.}}
#*{{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Thomas Macaulay}} (1800-1859)
#*:The great mass of the population abhorred Popery and '''adored''' Montouth.
#To be very [[fond]] of.
#*{{RQ:Chmbrs YngrSt|II}}
#*:"I ought to arise and go forth with timbrels and with dances; but, do you know, I am not inclined to revels? There has been a little&mdash;just a very little bit too much festivity so far&nbsp;&hellip;. Not that I don't '''adore''' dinners and gossip and dances; not that I do not love to pervade bright and glittering places.{{nb...}}"
#{{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[adorn]].
#*{{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*:Like to the hore / Congealed drops, which do the morn '''adore'''.

